Guided Exercise: Configure Identity Providers (HTPasswd)
Goal of This Exercise
You will:
1.	Create an HTPasswd file
2.	Store it inside a Kubernetes Secret
3.	Configure OAuth to use HTPasswd
4.	Create users
5.	Assign cluster-admin role
6.	Test access permissions
7.	Add users
8.	Update passwords
9.	Delete users
10.	Remove the identity provider
So the complete authentication lifecycle is covered.
________________________________________
2. Prepare the Lab Environment
Command:
lab start auth-providers
What it does
This command:
•	starts the OpenShift lab environment
•	ensures the cluster is reachable
•	creates required resources
Think of it like:
reset + prepare environment
________________________________________
3. Create the HTPasswd File
HTPasswd is a username + encrypted password file.
Example format:
username:hashedpassword
________________________________________
Create first user
htpasswd -c -B -b ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd new_admin redhat
Explanation
Option	Meaning
-c	create new file
-B	bcrypt password hashing
-b	password provided in command
Result file:
new_admin:$2y$05$snFFxG...
Password is encrypted.
________________________________________
Add second user
htpasswd -B -b ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd new_developer developer
Now the file contains:
new_admin:hash
new_developer:hash
Check file:
cat ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd
________________________________________
4. Login to OpenShift as Admin
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc login	login command
-u admin	username
-p redhatocp	password
https://...	API server
Now you have cluster admin privileges.
________________________________________
5. Create Secret for HTPasswd File
OpenShift cannot directly read files.
So we store the file inside a Kubernetes Secret.
Command:
oc create secret generic localusers \
--from-file htpasswd=~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
Explanation
Part	Meaning
secret generic	create a secret
localusers	secret name
--from-file	load file
htpasswd=	key name
openshift-config	namespace
Result:
secret/localusers created
________________________________________
6. Assign Cluster Admin Role
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin new_admin
Meaning
Give user full cluster control.
Equivalent to:
root user
Even though the user doesn't exist yet, the role binding is created.
Warning appears:
User 'new_admin' not found
This is normal.
User is created after first login.
________________________________________
7. Check Cluster Role Binding
Command:
oc get clusterrolebinding | grep ^cluster-admin
Then inspect the latest one:
oc describe clusterrolebinding cluster-admin-x
This shows:
User: new_admin
Role: cluster-admin
________________________________________
8. Configure OAuth Identity Provider
Now OpenShift must know how to authenticate users.
So we modify the OAuth configuration.
________________________________________
Export current OAuth configuration
oc get oauth cluster -o yaml > ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/oauth.yaml
This downloads the cluster OAuth config.
________________________________________
Add HTPasswd provider
Edit the file:
vim ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/oauth.yaml
Add:
- htpasswd:
    fileData:
      name: localusers
  mappingMethod: claim
  name: myusers
  type: HTPasswd
Explanation
Field	Meaning
htpasswd	authentication type
fileData	secret reference
name	identity provider name
mappingMethod	identity mapping
type	provider type
________________________________________
9. Apply OAuth Changes
oc replace -f ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/oauth.yaml
Output:
oauth.config.openshift.io/cluster replaced
Now OpenShift reloads authentication configuration.
________________________________________
10. Wait for OAuth Pod Restart
Authentication pods restart automatically.
Command:
watch oc get po -n openshift-authentication
Wait until:
oauth-openshift
STATUS: Running
This may take 3 minutes.
Stop watch:
CTRL + C
________________________________________
11. Login Using New User
oc login -u new_admin -p redhat
Now OpenShift:
User → OAuth → HTPasswd → authentication success
________________________________________
12. Verify Admin Permissions
Command:
oc get nodes
Output:
master01 Ready control-plane
If this works → user has cluster-admin.
________________________________________
13. Test Developer Permissions
Login as developer:
oc login -u new_developer -p developer
Try:
oc get nodes
Result:
Forbidden
Why?
Because:
new_developer ≠ cluster-admin
This confirms RBAC works.
________________________________________
14. View Users
Command:
oc get users
Example:
admin
new_admin
new_developer
Users are created after login.
________________________________________
15. View Identities
Command:
oc get identity
Example:
myusers:new_admin
myusers:new_developer
Identity format:
identityprovider:username
________________________________________
16. Add Another User (manager)
Extract secret:
oc extract secret/localusers -n openshift-config \
--to ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/ --confirm
This retrieves the htpasswd file from the secret.
________________________________________
Add user:
htpasswd -B -b ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd manager redhat
Check file:
cat htpasswd
Now it contains:
new_admin
new_developer
manager
________________________________________
17. Update Secret
oc set data secret/localusers \
--from-file htpasswd=~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
Meaning:
replace secret content
________________________________________
Wait again:
watch oc get pods -n openshift-authentication
________________________________________
18. Login as Manager
oc login -u manager -p redhat
________________________________________
19. Create Project
oc new-project auth-providers
Output:
project created
________________________________________
20. Test Permission Restriction
Login as developer:
oc login -u new_developer -p developer
Try deleting project:
oc delete project auth-providers
Result:
Forbidden
This proves RBAC restrictions.
________________________________________
21. Update Manager Password
Generate random password:
MANAGER_PASSWD="$(openssl rand -hex 15)"
Example result:
4f8e9c21d...
Update password:
htpasswd -B -b htpasswd manager ${MANAGER_PASSWD}
Update secret again:
oc set data secret/localusers \
--from-file htpasswd=htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
Wait for OAuth restart.
________________________________________
Login using new password:
oc login -u manager -p ${MANAGER_PASSWD}
________________________________________
22. Delete Manager User
Extract secret again:
oc extract secret/localusers -n openshift-config --to ~/DO280/labs/auth-providers/ --confirm
Delete entry:
htpasswd -D htpasswd manager
Update secret again.
________________________________________
Now login fails:
oc login -u manager
Result:
401 Unauthorized
________________________________________
23. Delete Identity
Find identity:
oc get identity | grep manager
Delete:
oc delete identity myusers:manager
________________________________________
24. Delete User
oc delete user manager
Check:
oc get users
Manager removed.
________________________________________
25. Remove Identity Provider
Edit OAuth:
oc edit oauth
Delete:
- htpasswd
Keep only:
LDAP
Save file.
________________________________________
Wait for authentication pod restart again.
________________________________________
26. Delete Secret
oc delete secret localusers -n openshift-config
________________________________________
27. Delete All Users
oc delete user --all
Delete identities:
oc delete identity --all
________________________________________
28. Finish Lab
lab finish auth-providers
This cleans the environment.
________________________________________
29. Full Architecture Flow
User login
     ↓
OAuth server
     ↓
HTPasswd identity provider
     ↓
Secret → htpasswd file
     ↓
Validate username/password
     ↓
User created
     ↓
RBAC roles applied
________________________________________
30. Most Important Commands for EX280
Create user:
htpasswd -B -b htpasswd user password
Create secret:
oc create secret generic localusers --from-file htpasswd=file
Extract secret:
oc extract secret/localusers
Update secret:
oc set data secret/localusers --from-file htpasswd=file
Delete user:
htpasswd -D htpasswd username
Assign cluster admin:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin user

